      "question": "If $\\sin \\theta = \\frac{1}{2}$ and $\\cos \\phi = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}$, where $\\theta$ and $\\phi$ are acute angles, then the value of $\\frac{\\tan \\theta + \\tan \\phi}{1 - \\tan \\theta \\tan \\phi}$ is:",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the value of $\\theta$ from $\\sin \\theta = \\frac{1}{2}$, which is $30^\\circ$.",
          "Identify the value of $\\phi$ from $\\cos \\phi = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}$, which is $45^\\circ$.",
          "Calculate $\\tan 30^\\circ = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}$ and $\\tan 45^\\circ = 1$.",
          "Substitute these values into the expression $\\frac{\\tan 30^\\circ + \\tan 45^\\circ}{1 - \\tan 30^\\circ \\tan 45^\\circ}$.",
          "Simplify the expression to get $\\frac{\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} + 1}{1 - \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}} = \\frac{1 + \\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{3} - 1}$.",
          "Rationalize the denominator to obtain $\\frac{(1 + \\sqrt{3})^2}{3 - 1} = \\frac{1 + 3 + 2\\sqrt{3}}{2} = 2 + \\sqrt{3}$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\sin \\theta = \\frac{1}{2} \\Rightarrow \\theta = 30^\\circ \\\\ \\cos \\phi = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\Rightarrow \\phi = 45^\\circ \\\\ \\tan \\theta = \\tan 30^\\circ = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}, \\tan \\phi = \\tan 45^\\circ = 1 \\\\ \\frac{\\tan \\theta + \\tan \\phi}{1 - \\tan \\theta \\tan \\phi} = \\frac{\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} + 1}{1 - (\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}})(1)} \\\\ = \\frac{\\frac{1+\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{3}}}{\\frac{\\sqrt{3}-1}{\\sqrt{3}}} = \\frac{1+\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{3}-1} \\\\ = \\frac{(\\sqrt{3}+1)(\\sqrt{3}+1)}{(\\sqrt{3}-1)(\\sqrt{3}+1)} = \\frac{3+1+2\\sqrt{3}}{3-1} = \\frac{4+2\\sqrt{3}}{2} = 2+\\sqrt{3}$"
      },
